body:
@paszczus as already mentioned by mtgap it is documented in the admin documentation he pointed to and also in the user documentation: http://doc.owncloud.org/server/5.0/user_manual/files/encryption.html

it is opt-in by purpose, because this feature can also be seen as a back door to access users encrypted data, that's why each user should decide actively to enable this feature. i'm not against some more visual information about this feature but i'm not sure if jan would like the idea of a pup-up dialog. :wink: 

@jancborchardt what do you think? do you think this could be useful and how would you integrate it?

@jancborchardt enabling/disabling encryption for individual users is not possible at the moment. i wouldn't go this way, this would open a lot of other problems, e.g. how would you handle file sharing if some users use encryption and some not?

i would also not like to give the admin the power to decide for all users to enable the recovery key or not. although in some use-cases this can be useful, e.g. think about company policies. but this shouldn't be the general behaviour for personal ownclouds. if it comes to security you always have to make a trade-off between security and convenience. you can't have 100% security and 100% convenience so we need to allow the user to adjust this ratio as it fits.

@paszczus thinking about it i recognised that we also don't "warn" the user during first log-in that he should set a valid email-address in the personal settings to be able to recover his log-in password in case of password loss. so maybe we simply have to expect that a new user will have a look at the settings to see how he can tweak his account? maybe it is also the job of the provider to tell such thinks the user at the beginning, e.g. in case of a service provider in the welcome message. actually he should also inform his user if encryption is enabled and maybe also about some other stuff.
